        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Correlator setup: We will use the FULL polarization mode, needed to detect the dust polarization.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Imaging requirement: We ask for an angular resolution of 1.4 arcsec, as a compromise between angular resolution and sensitivity. This will allow us to trace for the first time at high-angular resolution the morphology of the magnetic field towards the center of IRDCs (all previous observations have been performed with single-dish). We note that the SMA does not have the sensitivity to carry out polarimetric observation of IRDCs. The much higher image fidelity and sensitivity of ALMA will allow to detect the dust polarized emission. The dust continuum emission towards core SMA1 in Her 3a has a deconvolved size of about 5 arcsec at 1 mm (as measured with SMA; the decolvolved size of ALMA Cycle 0 is about 1.5 arcsec), well within the inner 1/3 of the ALMA primary beam (about 8"), as requested for polarization observations.

The Maximum Recoverable Scale at this frequency and angular resolution is of about 10 arcsec.

</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Required sensitivity: The total amount of time of 3 hours is constrained by ALMA to have a good parallactic angle coverage for the polarization calibrator. The rms achieved in this total time is 15 microJy/Beam or a 2% detection at 3-sigma for a dust emission of about 2.3 mJy/beam. Based on the ALMA Cycle 1 observations, the peak of the dust emission is expected to be 8 mJy/beam at 263 GHz and at 1.4 arcsec, so we will be able to detect a 2% dust polarization (160 microJy/beam) with a S/N of about 10.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Observing polarization at 263 GHz allows us to slightly gain in resolution (1.4") and in S/N for the same rms. The dust continuum emission flux of the core is proportional to the flux at 233 GHz multiplied by (263/233)^(2+beta), where beta=1.5 (Q. Zhang, private communication). Therefore, the flux is a factor of 1.5 higher at 263 than at 233 GHz. What is more, the atmospheric transmission is quite similar.  </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_NON_STD_CONT_FREQ</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
