    <prp:abstract>The main goal of this proposal is to study the initial stage of magnetic fields in IRDCs at high-angular resolution. To do this, we propose to observe with ALMA in Band 6 at 263 GHz and with an angular resolution of 1.4 arcsec the polarized dust emission of two IRDCs in different evolutionary phases: core SMA1 in Her 3a, a cold infrared-dark core with no signs of star formation, and core SMA1 in Her 4, a warm infrared-dark core that is associated at least with an embedded protostar as suggested by the presence of a compact SiO molecular outflow. Our goals are: 1) to trace for the first time at high-angular resolution the morphology of the magnetic field toward the center of IRDCs; 2) to study how the magnetic field changes with evolution, in particular with the onset of star formation, by comparing the magnetic field properties of SMA1 Her 3a and SMA1 Her 4; 3) to establish whether the absence of an internal source of radiation significantly affects the polarization efficiencies in the core (whether the center is unpolarized); and 4) to compare the morphology and properties of the magnetic field in IRDCs to those observed towards more evolved HMCs, like for example G31.41+0.31.
</prp:abstract>
